A priest in the Hagakure is recorded saying how a certain type of mushroom didn't grow on an island in Japan, so the people living there prayed and wished for it to appear so it soon did. When the folk prays and truly wishes for something together, it always comes true in the end

My favorite example is St. Porphyrios saying he wishes to place a water fountain in the middle of a woods so the birds could drink from it. The mineral of New Jerusalem amidst the barbarous plants and animals of the wilderness. But the peoples sometimes wish for other things too.

The Hagakure warns that disasters often follow rare omens like lightning in December, comets, unusual clouds, eclipses, etc. because the people expect and believe the omen to forecast a tragedy, so they summon it into reality with their fearful imagination. A Paracelsian concept.

Paracelsus has the general idea that all plagues, disasters, monsters are caused by someone's sick imagination or vice, especially where women live together. Thus he suggests the state hire certain men like himself to visit monasteries, brothels, etc. and keep them under control.
"Do you know anything else about Paracelsus other than the Miguel Serrano quote"

Believing such omens to be superstition is sign of decay, similar to how in Socratic Greece the doctrine of Bodily Resurrection was forgotten. Japanese belief that oarfish indicate a coming tsunami, certain cloud patterns & lights at dusk as premonitions for earthquakes are true.
